    id: "stonehenge",
    name: "Stonehenge",
    location: "Wiltshire, England",
    coordinates: [-1.8262, 51.1789],
    access: "Accessible",
    tags: ["Megalithic", "Celestial Alignment", "Sacred / Ritual"],
    hook: "Stones dragged from 150 miles away and joined with a precision that belongs in carpentry, not geology. We have been standing inside this circle for 5,000 years and still cannot say, with confidence, what we are standing in.",
    record: "Stonehenge was constructed in stages between approximately 3000 and 2000 BCE on Salisbury Plain in Wiltshire, England. The monument consists of an outer ring of sarsen stones — the largest weighing approximately 25 tons — and an inner arrangement of bluestones weighing up to 4 tons each. The bluestones were sourced from the Preseli Hills in Wales, approximately 240 kilometers away. Recent excavation at Waun Mawn in Wales suggests the bluestones were part of an earlier stone circle that was dismantled and relocated. The sarsen stones are joined using mortise-and-tenon joints carved directly into the stone. The structure aligns with the midsummer sunrise and midwinter sunset.",
    mystery: "The bluestones didn’t start here.\nThey were part of an earlier circle — assembled, used, then dismantled and moved 150 miles to this location.\nThe larger stones were shaped with mortise-and-tenon joints. A woodworking technique. Applied to stone. At this scale.\nThe structure aligns with the midsummer sunrise and midwinter sunset.\nTransport. Joinery. Alignment.\nAll of it fixed in this one place.",
    perspective: "The site is smaller than you expect. The presence isn't.\nYou're kept at a distance — the path circles the stones without getting close. At first it feels like a limitation. Then it becomes the point.\nStep back. Let the whole structure sit against the sky.\nSome of these stones were already standing somewhere else. Already part of a circle. Someone took that circle apart and moved it here.\nThey didn't just want stones. They wanted those stones.",
    travelReality: "HOW TO GET THERE\nStonehenge sits in the English countryside about 2 hours southwest of London. The simplest option is to rent a car and drive — it gives you control over timing and avoids group schedules. There are also frequent organized tours departing from London, often bundled with Bath or Windsor. Public transport is possible (train to Salisbury, then bus or taxi), but it adds time and coordination.\n\nWHAT TO EXPECT ON ARRIVAL\nThis is a tightly managed site. You don’t walk freely among the stones — access is restricted to a circular path set at a distance. The monument itself is smaller than many expect, but the setting matters — open land, low horizon, and wind moving across the plain. There’s a visitor center, shuttle transport to the stones, and a steady flow of visitors. It does not feel remote, but it does hold presence if you give it a moment.\n\nHOW LONG TO SPEND\nOne to two hours is enough for most visitors. The walking path around the stones is straightforward and doesn’t take long. If you’re interested in the surrounding landscape or the visitor center exhibits, you can extend that slightly, but this is not a full-day site.\n\nBEST TIME TO VISIT\nEarly morning or late afternoon to avoid peak crowds. Midday can feel crowded, especially in summer. Winter visits are quieter but colder and often wet. The solstices draw large crowds and a very different atmosphere — more event than visit.\n\nPHYSICAL DEMANDS\nLow. The site is flat with well-maintained paths. Weather is the main factor — wind, rain, and mud can affect comfort more than terrain.\n\nESSENTIAL TIPS\nManage expectations — you won’t be walking up to or touching the stones unless you’ve booked special access well in advance. Bring layers; the weather shifts quickly and the site is fully exposed. If you want a quieter experience, walk the full loop rather than stopping at the main viewing point. Consider combining the visit with nearby Avebury — a larger, less restricted stone circle where you can walk among the stones.",
