    hook: "A farmer draining a pond uncovered a doorway into something that shouldn't exist. Twenty-four massive caverns carved from solid sandstone, every surface grooved with inhuman precision. No record. No legend. No memory. Someone hollowed out a mountain and then history swallowed the evidence whole.",
    record: "The Longyou Caves are located near the village of Longyou in Zhejiang Province, China, approximately 300 kilometers southwest of Shanghai. The caves were discovered in 1992 when a local farmer pumped water from what was assumed to be a natural pond. Twenty-four caverns have been identified, carved from siltstone at varying depths. The walls, ceilings, and pillars of\neach chamber are covered in uniform parallel grooves — the same spacing and angle repeated across every surface. The total volume of removed stone has been estimated at nearly one million cubic meters. No historical records, inscriptions, or oral traditions describing the caves or their construction have been identified.",
    mystery: "In 1992, a farmer pumped water from what he assumed was a natural pond. Beneath it was a carved chamber. Then another. Eventually 24 were identified.\nMassive spaces cut from the rock, their walls, ceilings, and pillars covered in parallel grooves. The pattern repeats — same spacing, same angles, across every surface.\nNearly a million cubic meters of stone removed.\nNo records describe the work. No account names the builders.\nThe chambers were finished. Sealed.\nAnd left with nothing above them to remember they were there.",
    perspective: "The caves were found by accident. A farmer draining what he thought was a pond.\nUnderneath: a carved chamber. Then 23 more.\nWhen you get inside, ignore the scale for a moment.\nGet close to the wall. Look at the grooves — parallel lines cut across every surface, ceiling included. Same spacing. Same angle. Chamber after chamber.\nRun your fingers along them if you're allowed.\nThey don't vary. They don't drift.\nNo record names them. No account describes them.\nTouch the wall and consider that.",
    travelReality: "HOW TO GET THERE\nThe caves are near the village of Longyou in Zhejiang Province, roughly 300 kilometers southwest of Shanghai. The most practical route is to fly into Hangzhou and then take a bus or hire a car for the remaining 150 kilometers — about two and a half hours by road. There is no direct train to Longyou village. A Mandarin-speaking guide or driver is strongly recommended unless you’re confident navigating rural Chinese infrastructure on your own.\n\nWHAT TO EXPECT ON ARRIVAL\nThe caves are a managed tourist site with a visitor center and walkways installed inside the caverns. Only a handful of the 24 caves are open to the public. The interior is vast and cool — the grooved surfaces that cover every wall, ceiling, and pillar are immediately striking in person. Lighting is installed but the atmosphere retains a genuinely unsettling quality. The site is not heavily touristed by Western visitors, so English signage and guides are limited.\n\nHOW LONG TO SPEND\nTwo to three hours is sufficient for the open caves and visitor center. The caverns themselves don’t take long to walk through, but the surface textures reward slow, close observation. If you’ve traveled this far to see them, don’t rush it.\n\nBEST TIME TO VISIT\nSpring (April–May) or autumn (September–October) offer the most comfortable weather in Zhejiang Province. Summers are hot and humid. The caves maintain a cool interior temperature year-round, so the season matters more for the travel than for the site itself.\n\nPHYSICAL DEMANDS\nLow. The caves are at a low elevation with installed walkways and stairs. No climbing or scrambling required. The main challenge is the journey to get there, not the site itself.\n\nESSENTIAL TIPS\nBring a good camera — the grooved surfaces photograph well but the interior lighting is dim, so a phone may struggle. A small flashlight helps for examining surface details up close. Don’t expect extensive English-language interpretation at the site; do your reading before you arrive. The village of Longyou itself is a quiet rural town with limited accommodation — most visitors base themselves in Hangzhou and make a day trip.",
