    id: "goseck",
    name: "The Goseck Circle",
    location: "Goseck, Germany",
    coordinates: [11.8646, 51.1981],
    access: "Accessible",
    tags: ["Celestial Alignment", "Sacred / Ritual"],
    hook: "Two gates in a timber circle, both aimed at the winter solstice — not roughly, not approximately, but with a precision that turns coincidence into intention. Seven thousand years ago, someone was reading the sky like a clock. We just found the clock.",
    record: "The Goseck Circle dates to approximately 4900 BCE, located in eastern Germany near the city of Halle. The site consists of concentric rings of earth and timber palisades with three gates, two of which align with the sunrise and sunset of the winter solstice. The original structure was identified through aerial survey before excavation and has since been reconstructed on its original foundations. The enclosure measures approximately 75 meters in diameter. Goseck is one of several Neolithic circular enclosures — known as Kreisgrabenanlagen — found across Germany and Austria. The Nebra Sky Disk, dating to roughly 1600 BCE, was discovered approximately 25 kilometers away.",
    mystery: "4900 BCE.\nAt Goseck, the southern gates of a circular enclosure align with the sunrise and sunset of the winter solstice.\nIt works.\nStand inside the circle and look through the openings. The sun rises where the structure tells it to. It sets where it’s expected to.\nThis wasn’t guessed. It was placed.\nAnd it wasn’t done once. Similar circles appear across the region, repeating the same idea.\nThe pattern is already there — fully formed.",
    perspective: "What’s here now is a reconstruction — timber palisades rebuilt on the original foundation. You’re not looking at the thing itself. You’re looking at the shape of it.\nBut stand inside and face the southern gates at the solstice, and the shape is enough.\nThe sun rises through one opening. Sets through the other.\nThe posts are new. The alignment isn’t.\nYou’re standing in something that still knows where the sun will be.",
    travelReality: "HOW TO GET THERE\nGoseck Circle is located in eastern Germany, about a 30-minute drive from the city of Halle or just over an hour from Leipzig. The site is in a rural area with limited public transport options, so driving is the most practical way to reach it.\n\nWHAT TO EXPECT ON ARRIVAL\nThe site is a reconstructed circular enclosure made of wooden palisades and earthworks. It sits in an open field with minimal surrounding infrastructure. What you’re seeing is a modern reconstruction based on archaeological findings — the original structure dates back over 7,000 years and was identified through aerial surveys before excavation. There is no large visitor center or extensive interpretation on-site. The structure itself is simple in appearance — its significance comes from its alignment and age rather than visual complexity.\n\nHOW LONG TO SPEND\n30 minutes to an hour is sufficient. The site is small and quickly accessible.\n\nBEST TIME TO VISIT\nAny time of year is viable, though clear days make the layout and alignments easier to understand. The winter solstice period is of particular interest due to the site’s solar alignment, but there are no large-scale events compared to more famous sites.\n\nPHYSICAL DEMANDS\nLow. The terrain is flat and easy to walk.\n\nESSENTIAL TIPS\nDo some reading before you arrive — without context, the site can feel underwhelming. Walk the perimeter to understand the full layout. Combine the visit with other nearby sites if you’re in the region, as Goseck alone is a short stop.",
